Lizeka Tandwa, news24Joburg Mayor Herman Mashaba (File, Karabo Ngoepe, News24) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories EFF volunteers and police clashed outside a council meeting in Johannesburg on Tuesday.WATCHJohannesburg - Johannesburg Mayor Herman Mashaba made ambitious promises in his first inaugural council address on Tuesday, vowing to cut unemployment by 6%, or resign.&nbsp;"If I don't bring down unemployment by 6% in five years, I will voluntarily step down in five years. This demonstrates my commitment to the people of this city."He promised to end corruption in the City&rsquo;s administration and said he had already sent a number of cases to be investigated.Mashaba told the council that job creation would be a core priority in his administration.He had reached an agreement with his department heads that all plans and policies be aligned with the goal of achieving a 5% economic growth rate for the city.&nbsp;He said his officials had presented him with a projected target of 2.5% economic growth. "This is simply not good enough. Because to accept 2.5% economic growth would mean we accept that we will not make a dent in the number of unemployed people in our city. I cannot accept this."&nbsp;He also promised to stabilise and strengthen waste removal company Pikitup.Mashaba promised to clear a backlog of 2 080 illegal dumping sites. The City would begin enforcing by-laws at these sites with the help of metro police, he said.&nbsp; 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.